<td data-index="470"><div class="right" data-index="471">2,000,000</div></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</figure>
<p data-index="472"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="12-8" id="Page_12-8" data-index="473"></span>The preceding example assumed no residual value for the customer list. But what if Green Market determines that it can sell the list for $60,000 to another company at the end of three years? In that case, Green Market should subtract this residual value from the cost in order to determine the amortization expense for each year. Amortization expense would be $1,980,000, as shown in <a class="blue" id="c12-fig-0002-1" href="#c12-fig-0002" data-index="474" data-section-index="22" data-section-idref="c12-fig-0002" data-target-data-index="476"><b data-index="475">Illustration 12.2</b></a>.</p>
<figure id="c12-fig-0002" data-index="476">
